top_comments.comment: I feel proud whenever I recognize a piece

comments_since_last_sample.body: Ok so this is why the views on my le sapin video spiked a bit LOL
A new Sibelius piece to listen to? You've made up for the lack of Bartok on the list guys :D

That Sibelius miniature was sitting in my playlist for a while. So simple, yet so enjoyable.
Talking about Sibelius - he wrote String quartet in D minor, which is also really cool.
I love it in Emerson String Quartet interpretation. Can be found in their "Intimate voices" album. That album also has Grieg - String Quartet in G minor, which is also sooooo beautiful!
"Lord let me know mine end" is a golden find related with Psalm 39 prayer. This is one of the reasons why I love this channel apart from hilarious laughter. always something great to discover... 👏

And it gets worse when composers work on each other's pieces.  Liszt has a version of Beethoven's fifth symphony which is fit to make one give up piano.  Then Pablo de Sarasate - Les Adieux for Violin and Piano, Op. 9  which starts out easy and gets SOOOO hard, later on.
You forgot me! I’m disappointed in you TwoSet!
If you want unknown composers check those two : Cécile Chaminade and Charles-Valentin Alkan

Composers you probably never heard of and their works

Heinrich von Herzogenberg - Symphonies & Violin Concerto
Karl Goldmark - Symphonic poems
Louise Farrenc - Symphonies & Overtures
Luigi Cherubini - Masses (Requiem Mass for Louis XVI in C minor, in particular)
Christian Sinding - Symphonies

The Strauss Family contemporaries in light music (waltzes, polkas, marches, etc.) and operetta

I feel proud whenever I recognize a piece
I need calming piano pieces that I have never heard before. ( sibelius was a good find.. 👌
Liszt's 2nd Piano Concerto is so painfully underrated, that a lot of people don't even know it exists.
